Societal Biases in Survivor

Final Project
Data Science 1 with R (STAT 301-1)

Caroline Corr

Overview

It has long been said that Survivor as an institution reflects the cultural climate of our society. As a reality show made up of everyday people, it naturally follows that the biases that impact our society would also spill over into the game. Survivor is an intensely social game: it requires you to make your competitors like you and respect your gameplay enough that they will vote for you to win after all of the deceit and âstrategeryâ it took to get yourself to the final 3.

Since your fate in the game ultimately depends on the feelings and opinions of oneâs fellow competitors, I am interested in assessing how demographic information is related to the results of the game and the state of the competition over time. For my analysis, I am seeking to uncover any potential relationships between age, gender, race, and sexuality and how they impact the individual contestantâs performance on the show. I am interested in how these relationships could reveal bias both on the level of casting and individual performance in the game.

This exploratory data analysis (EDA) utilizes Justin Veinerâs Survivor (CBS) Dataset, sourced from kaggle.com. The dataset includes three tables for information concerning individual contestants, seasons, and pre- and post-merge tribes. Since the crux of this EDA is based on demographic information, only the contestant and season tables were used.

Link to Dataset

Data Overview

Contestant Table

The contestants table includes 785 observations, one for each contestants on Survivor seasons 1 through 43. There are 32 variables that reflect both in-game qualities and demographic information such as age, gender, race/ethnicity, and sexuality. There are 9 character variables, one date variable, and 22 numeric variables. Over the course of this EDA, some demographic variables were combined and converted into one character variable. These cases will be identified as they arise throughout the EDA for clarity and transparency. This data is very tidy and there is no glaring missingness issue, for the variables that have missing values such as num_jury_votes and tribe2/tribe3 can be explained by the fact that contestants who are eliminated before the final tribal council (FTC) do not receive jury votes, and not all contestants make it far enough in the game to belong to a second or third tribe.

Season Table

The seasons table includes 43 observations, one for each season of Survivor. There are 22 variables that describe both the events of the season and the demographic composition of each cast, with 3 character and 19 numeric. There is no missing data within this table.

Assessing Bias in Survivor

One of the most glaring biases I have witnessed as a long-time fan of the show is age. During the early part of the game where tribe strength is a priority, older contestants are often voted out early due to the perception that their age would make them a liability in physical challenges. Let us now turn to the data to uncover the presence and magnitude of this perceived bias.

Contestant Age

Univariate Analyses

FigureÂ 1 demonstrates how the distribution of contestant ages is strongly right skewed with most contestants falling in the age range from 20 to 30. This indicates that the showrunners are casting more young people, but it is also possible that less older adults audition to be on the show in the first place.

TableÂ 1 reinforces this pattern with helpful summary statistics concerning the age of Survivor contestants. While 31 may be quite young in the real world, it is considered middle-aged on the show! This reveals how older people are underrepresented on the casting level, but what about biases existing inside the realm of the show? Letâs investigate how age comes into play amidst the Survivor winnersâ circle:

FigureÂ 2 appears to follow a similarly right-skewed distribution as FigureÂ 1. Ergo, older members of society are not only less likely to be on the show in the first place, but they are seemingly at a similar disadvantage even after being cast. However, as previously mentioned, it is possible that this disparity could be a result of older people merely not auditioning at the same volume as younger people. To better understand how age functions as a bias on the show, we need to see how it interacts with other variables.

Bivariate Analyses

Before we delve deeper into the bias of the competition, we should first explore how age interacts with another demographic variable: namely, gender.

Here, we witness a disparity between the distributions of contestant age within each gender. Men and women are cast equally, but FigureÂ 3 suggests that male contestants tend to be slightly older.

Note: Within this dataset, only one contestant is coded as identifying as non-binary, and this contestant has been omitted from all explorations involving contestant gender. This contestant was not excluded for any reason other than the fact that this sample size of 1 is not large enough to generate any relevant insights concerning non-binary players.

FigureÂ 4 demonstrates a bimodal distribution for the final placements of contestants older than the median age of 31 (see TableÂ 1), while the distribution is fairly uniform for contestants belonging to the younger age group. Older contestants witness spikes around the 15th to 20th place range which supports my hypothesis that older tribe members are often voted out in the early stages of the game in order to cut out the physically weaker members. The other spike spanning from the finalists to ~7th place range indicates that older contestants who make it past to The Merge tend to make a deeper run in the game.

Note: The Merge is the halfway point in the game where all of the tribes are combined into one large tribe. This typically occurs when there are 12 players left in the game.

We now see how age interacts with placement in the grand scheme of the show, but it is also worth considering how age has functioned as a bias throughout Survivorâs 20+ year tenure.

FigureÂ 5 shows how the median contestant age has remained fairly constant over 43 seasons of Survivor, with season 40 being starkly older than all of its predecessors. This could be because season 40 was Survivorâs iconic Winners at War season which would naturally involve older, veteran players.

Note: Seeing as the age distribution is right-skewed (see FigureÂ 1), the median was selected as a more appropriate measure of center than mean.

FigureÂ 6 shows how finalist ages are similarly fairly consistent with the wider distribution for all contestants, but it is worth noting that the LOESS curve is located slightly above the median age of 31. This suggests that throughout the seasons, contestants closest to the median age are more likely to make it to FTC.

To assess how age potentially functions as a bias at FTC, I calculated the quartiles of contestant age and created a new variable that sorted each contestant into an age cohort that corresponds to each quartile (e.g., 18-26 is 0 to Q1, 27-31 is Q1 to Q2, and so on). TableÂ 2 summarizes the mean jury votes received according to each cohort of finalists, revealing that the 32-40 age range receives the most votes on average. Here, jury votes function as a measure of the way a finalistâs performance is perceived by their fellow competitors. Therefore, a higher number of jury votes is associated with a stronger overall performance.

Multivariate Analyses

As noted in FigureÂ 3, male contestants tend to be older than their female counterparts. Letâs see how gender interacts with some previously investigated variables that are indicative of biases both in the game and by the casting team.

FigureÂ 7 takes the median age of all contestants belonging to each gender and finishing placement. This chart supports the findings of FigureÂ 3 and FigureÂ 4, for male contestants are generally older, and older contestants are more likely to be eliminated before The Merge than younger contestants regardless of gender.

FigureÂ 8 reveals an interesting development in recent seasons: the age gap between men and women is shrinking. However, the pattern found in FigureÂ 3 has seemingly held strong over the years, for not one season deviates from the trend of male contestants being generally older than female contestants.

This exploration of age has enlightened us to a multitude of patterns. On the casting level, we have learned that older people are consistently underrepresented on the show, male contestants tend to be older than female contestants, and this gendered age gap appears to be closing in the new era of Survivor. Within the show, we see that older contestants are more likely to be eliminated early on, but they are also more likely to reach the end should they survive through The Merge. Additionally, contestants nearest the median age of 31 tend to have the most success on the show.

Let us now turn to a new potential source of bias: race and ethnicity.

Contestant Race/Ethnicity

In recent years, CBS has launched a diversity initiative for all of its unscripted reality shows, including Survivor. While this initiative is a great start to ensure proper representation on the network, it does not eliminate the interpersonal biases that influence the results of the show. The following explorations intend to gauge the showâs commitment to diversity on the casting level and how race and ethnicity function as a source of bias within the game itself.

Univariate Analyses

Letâs first take a look at the breakdown of race/ethnicity on the casting level:

Clearly, caucasian people make up the vast majority of Survivor contestants. How about the winners?

This subset of contestants follows a very similar distribution. FigureÂ 9 and FigureÂ 10 demonstrate a potentially misleading narrative, for it is important to remember that not all racial/ethnic identities are equally represented in our society as a whole. To correct for this, letâs compare how each race/ethnicity is represented on Survivor to the national population estimate.

TableÂ 3 and TableÂ 4 draw from US Census information concerning the national breakdown of each racial identity compared to how each is represented on Survivor.

On the casting level, caucasian people are the most overrepresented, while African American and Asian American people are represented fairly proportionally in relation to the national composition of these racial groups. The most underrepresented group are Latin Americans, who are cast 12.37% less than they should be according to the US Census.

Considering the winnersâ circle paints a slightly different picture. While caucasian contestants are winning at a higher rate than their representation suggests and Asian American contestants are winning at a rate that is on-par with their composition, African American and even moreso Latin American contestants are winning less.

Bivariate Analyses

FigureÂ 13 demonstrates the gender breakdown of each ethnicity, with TableÂ 5 providing the numerical summary. African American men and women are approximately equally represented, but there are larger disparities for Caucasian, Latin American, and Asian American contestants. Far more white men than women have been cast for the show, and the opposite can be said for Latin Americans and Asian Americans.

FigureÂ 12 nicely summarizes the percentage of the cast identifying as POC (people of color) throughout the showâs run. There appears to be a major shift towards a higher commitment to diversity occurring around the time of season 25âs airing in late 2012.

FigureÂ 13 shows each race/ethnicityâs placement density. The distributions for Caucasian and African American contestants generally follow a unimodal shape, with the highest likelihood of elimination occurring around the time of The Merge.

Itâs a different story for Asian American and Latin American contestants, as these distributions are bimodal, with peaks before and after The Merge. This suggests that contestants belonging to these ethnicities have been eliminated in the early game and the end game at higher volumes than in the middle of the game.

Now that we can see how each race/ethnicity is represented on the show and how the showâs diversity has changed over time, letâs take a look at how this variable could potentially influence the game itself.

FigureÂ 14 provides insight into how contestants of each race/ethnicity are received by the final jury of their peers at the end of the game. Interestingly, Latin American finalists average the highest amount of jury votes, but Caucasian and African American contestants tend to win by the highest margins.

An interesting dynamic that arises in the endgame of Survivor is the reliance on âgoats.â Goats are contestants that are brought to the end by their allies based off of the perception that the goatâs poor gameplay will make the other finalists look better to the jury. Looking at this graphic, if we consider finalists falling in the first quartile of their ethnic group to be goats, it is telling that Latin American and Caucasian goats have received more votes than Asian American or African American goats.

TableÂ 6 reveals the average votes received by finalists from each race/ethnic group. This reflects the findings of FigureÂ 14, but it is important to add the goat dynamic into our understanding of this breakdown. To correct for 0 vote/losing finalists, letâs see how this spread changes when we only look at votes received by winners of the show.

When we only consider the winners, we see that it is actually African American and Latin American winners who have won by the greatest margins!

Multivariate Analyses

Much like our assessment of how age functions as a source of bias in Survivor, it is important to remember that gender is often an important determinant that interacts with other variables to create bias.

FigureÂ 15 shows us how the distribution of placement according to ethnicity changes depending on gender. While all female contestants regardless of race/ethnicity follow a bimodal distribution with peaks in the early and endgames, the same can only be said for Asian American men. Every other male ethnicity is approximately unimodal, with most eliminations occurring around The Merge.

This could potentially reflect how tribes tend to vote out the players they perceive to be weaker in the early stages of the game, while after The Merge, the physically strongest players become challenge threats and are eliminated as soon as they lose immunity. These tendencies often fall along gendered lines within the show, as the women are seen as weaker and the men are thought to be stronger.

FigureÂ 16 demonstrates how the number of contestants belonging to each race/ethnic group has changed from season to season. This reflects the findings of FigureÂ 12, but it also enlightens us to the changes within each gender. African American men have witnessed a sharper increase in casting than their female counterparts, while the number of Asian American women cast is decreasing as opposed to Asian American males who are seeing a gradual increase in their representation.

Race and ethnicity function in several ways in the world of Survivor. On the casting level, we have learned that while African and Asian Americans are relatively fairly represented, Caucasian people are starkly overcast, and Latin Americans are quite underrepresented, particularly the men. While Survivor has become far more diverse over the course of its 43 seasons, these figures demonstrate that there is still plenty of work to be done.

On the interpersonal level, there is some evidence for the presence of racial/ethnic biases influencing the game. POC contestants (women in particular) are generally eliminated at higher rates during the beginning of the game, and African and Asian Americans tend to receive less votes at FTC than Caucasian and Latin American finalists. However, of the winners, African and Latin Americans have won by the highest margins.

Letâs now take a look at the last potential source of bias in this EDA: gender and sexuality.

Contestant Gender/Sexuality

On each season of Survivor, there is an even number of male and female contestants, so it is no question that both are equally represented on the show. However, that does not guarantee that both are regarded equally.

Univariate Analyses

FigureÂ 17 shows how the Survivor winnersâ circle is dominated by men. We will explore the relationship between gender and final placement in the Bivariate Analysis section.

To gauge whether or not LGBTQ+ contestants are fairly represented on the show, the percentage of LGBTQ+ contestants is compared to the national percentage according to the 2024 Gallup Poll conducted by Jeffrey M. Jones. TableÂ 8 interestingly suggests that LGBTQ+ contestants are actually slightly overrepresented in comparison to the national breakdown!

When only winners are considered, itâs a different story. In fact, only 2 LGBTQ+ contestants have won the show in 43 seasons.

Bivariate Analyses

Gender and sexuality go hand in hand when it comes to potential bias. First, letâs see how these two factors interact on the casting level.

As we can see in FigureÂ 18, LGBTQ+ men have been cast at a higher volume than queer women.

While men and women are cast equally, FigureÂ 19 shows how these genders experience the game in near-opposite ways. The female curve is bimodal, suggesting that women are more likely to be eliminated in the early game or the end game. The opposite can be said for male contestants, for they follow a unimodal distribution that reinforces how they are more likely to be eliminated during the early Merge where physical threats are targeted.

The same cannot be said for sexuality, for LGBTQ+ contestants follow a unimodal curve while that of the non-LGBTQ+ player distribution is more uniform. While LGBTQ+ contestants tend have been eliminated at the highest volume in the mid game, non-LGBTQ+ players are eliminated at similar volumes across almost the entire duration of the game. This could be explained by the mere fact that there are far more cis/hetero contestants than not, so data concerning LGBTQ+ contestants is limited.

FigureÂ 21 follows a very similar curve to FigureÂ 12, demonstrating how Survivor has gotten a lot more diverse since its 20th season. In fact, since around season 30, LGBTQ+ contestants have actually been strongly overrepresented on the show (according to the national percentage shown in TableÂ 8)

FigureÂ 22 demonstrates how male finalists tend to receive more jury votes than their female counterparts. Interestingly, if we continue qualifying finalists within the first quartile as goats, it appears that male and female goats both tend to receive the same amount of votes.

TableÂ 10 and TableÂ 11 reinforce these findings from FigureÂ 22, for not only do male finalists tend to receive more votes, but they also tend to win by a considerably higher margin than female finalists.

When it comes to sexuality, this relationship is harder to parse due to a limited sample size of LGBTQ+ finalists and winners. Visuals concerning how LGBTQ+ contestants are received at FTC compared to non-LGBTQ+ players can be seen in Appendix: Extra Explorations.

Multivariate Analyses

Much like the narrative seen in FigureÂ 15, female contestants witness a bimodal distribution concerning their placement while the male distribution is unimodal, regardless of race, ethnicity, or sexuality. However, it is worth noting that the non-LGBTQ+ curves are slightly wider than the LGBTQ+ curve. While this does not suggest much in-game bias, it does testify to the smaller pool of LGBTQ+ contestants.

While the curves in FigureÂ 24 are subtle, there are some interesting patterns to tease out. It appears that there has never been more than one LGBTQ+ contestant of each gender on any season of the show up to season 43, and while LGBTQ+ men are represented in the cast quite consistently, there have been seasons where not a single LGBTQ+ woman is featured on the cast.

On the casting level, there is not much evidence for bias. Men and women are cast equally for the show, and LGBTQ+ people are fairly represented according to the national composition.

On the interpersonal level, the data does suggest some degree of bias against female contestants. They are more likely to be eliminated in the early game based off of the perception that they are weaker in tribe challenges, and they tend to receive less jury votes at FTC than male finalists. For LGBTQ+ contestants, it does not seem appropriate to draw any conclusions due to the small sample size of LGBTQ+ finalists and winners.

Conclusion

From this exploration, it is clear to see that demographic information plays a role in generating bias on behalf of the showrunners but also fellow contestants within the game.

On the casting level, we have learned that older generations, Latin Americans, and LGBTQ+ women are the most underrepresented on the show.

On the interpersonal level, there is the most evidence for bias against older contestants, Latin and Asian American contestants, and women in general, regardless of age, race/ethnicity, or sexuality.

Throughout this exploration, it became abundantly clear that gender was the ultimate source of bias within the show. This is an interesting revelation, seeing as gender does not bias the casting process in the slightest. Regardless of age, race/ethnicity, or sexuality, female contestants have historically been eliminated earlier, won the show less, and received less jury votes at FTC. I believe this can be attributed to the tendency for people to perceive women who possess the traits often associated with good Survivor gameplay - assertiveness, decisiveness, and manipulation - in a less favorable light than men who behave similarly.

In the future, I would be interested in delving deeper into how sexuality functions as a form of bias. This dataset only codes contestants as LGBTQ+ or not, and it does not provide any further information into specific LGBTQ+ identities. Although this does not solve the issue of small sample size, I believe more meaningful insights could be drawn given more specific information.
